align: thumb|right|upright=1|Meeting in the Hall of Knights in The Hague, during the congress (9 May 1948)  A pivotal moment in European integration was the Hague Congress of May 1948, as it led to the creation of the European Movement International, the College of Europe   and most importantly to the founding of the Council of Europe on the 5th of May 1949 (today its Europe day). The Council of Europe was the first institution to bring the sovereign nations of Europe together, raising great hopes and fevered debates in the following two years for further European integration.
